1.Node Selector and Node Affinity in Kubernetes (Complete Explanation):

1.Node Selector:
-------------

These topics are very commonly asked in Kubernetes interviews, especially together with Taints & Tolerations.

A good way to remember them is:

Feature	Purpose
Node Selector	Choose a node using simple labels
Node Affinity	Choose a node using advanced rules
Taints	Keep unwanted Pods away from a node
Tolerations	Allow a Pod onto a tainted node
Why do we need Node Selector?

Suppose your cluster has three worker nodes.

                Kubernetes Cluster

                  Scheduler
                      |
        ---------------------------------
        |               |               |
     Worker-1       Worker-2        Worker-3

Imagine:

Worker-1 → SSD Disk
Worker-2 → GPU
Worker-3 → High Memory

Now you have an AI application.

Where should it run?

Obviously:

GPU Node

But Kubernetes doesn't know that.

Without instructions, the scheduler may place it anywhere.

AI Pod

↓

Worker-1 ❌

This is where Node Selector comes in.

What is Node Selector?

A Node Selector is the simplest way to tell Kubernetes:

"Run this Pod only on nodes with this label."

Step 1: Label the Node

Suppose Worker-2 has a GPU.

Add a label:

kubectl label node worker-2 gpu=true

Verify:

kubectl get nodes --show-labels

Example:

worker-1

disk=ssd
worker-2

gpu=true
worker-3

memory=high
Step 2: Create the Pod
apiVersion: v1
kind: Pod
metadata:
  name: ai-app

spec:

  nodeSelector:
    gpu: "true"

  containers:
  - name: app
    image: nginx

