Interview Comparison Table
Feature	Node Selector	Node Affinity
Complexity	Simple	Advanced
Label matching	Exact only	Many operators
AND/OR support	No	Yes
Preferred rules	No	Yes
Required rules	No	Yes
Recommended	Small clusters	Production
Node Selector vs Node Affinity vs Taints
Feature	Purpose
Node Selector	Choose a node by exact label.
Node Affinity	Choose a node using flexible matching rules (required or preferred).
Taint	Repel Pods from a node unless they have permission.
Toleration	Permit a Pod to run on a tainted node.

Think of scheduling in two steps:

Selection: Which nodes are eligible?
Node Selector or Node Affinity answers this.
Permission: Is the Pod allowed onto that node?
Taints and Tolerations answer this.
Complete Scheduling Flow
                    Pod Created
                         │
                         ▼
        Does the node match NodeSelector/Affinity?
                         │
              No ─────────────► Skip node
                         │
                        Yes
                         │
                         ▼
              Does the node have a taint?
                         │
               No ─────────────► Schedule Pod
                         │
                        Yes
                         │
                         ▼
          Does the Pod have a matching toleration?
                         │
               No ─────────────► Reject node
                         │
                        Yes
                         │
                         ▼
                  Schedule the Pod
Hands-on Example Using Your EKS Cluster

You have two worker nodes:

ip-192-168-17-51.ec2.internal
ip-192-168-35-138.ec2.internal

You can practice as follows:

1. Label one node
kubectl label node ip-192-168-17-51.ec2.internal gpu=true
2. Verify
kubectl get nodes --show-labels
3. Create a Pod with a nodeSelector
apiVersion: v1
kind: Pod
metadata:
  name: gpu-pod
  namespace: canary-ns
spec:
  nodeSelector:
    gpu: "true"
  containers:
  - name: nginx
    image: nginx

Check where it landed:

kubectl get pod gpu-pod -o wide -n canary-ns

It should run on ip-192-168-17-51.ec2.internal.

Then replace nodeSelector with nodeAffinity to achieve the same result using:

requiredDuringSchedulingIgnoredDuringExecution

This hands-on comparison is one of the best ways to understand why Node Affinity is considered the more flexible, production-ready option.





